What we really need is some way to access each array element without having to explicitly list each one.Arrays and loopsIn previous lessons, we noted that array subscripts do not need to be constant expressions -- they can be runtime expressions. This means we can use the value of a variable as an index.Also note that the array indices used in the average calculation of the previous example are an ascending sequence: 0, 1, 2, 3, 4. Therefore, if we had some way to set a variable to values 0, 1, 2, 3, and 4 in sequence, then we could just use that variable as our array index instead of literals. And we already know how to do that -- with a for-loop.Related contentWe covered for loops in lesson8.10 -- For statements.Let’s rewrite the above example using a for-loop, where the loop variable is used as the array index:#include <iostream>
